title: IKESU: Music player for listening to "season" music
title_en: IKESU: Music player for listening to "season" music
abstract: 本研究はPC上での音楽再生において利用者が継続的に「旬」な音楽を発見して聴けるインタフェースを提案している。本研究はアルバム単位の可視化と収集型プレイリスト、未聴曲優先のシャッフルや検索クエリの重み付けなどを実装した試作システムを提示し、探索的な発見と新奇性の維持を目指した機能を示した。
abstract_en: This study proposes an interface for PC music playback that helps users continuously discover and listen to "seasonal" music. This study implemented a prototype collection-based player with album-level visualization, shuffle favoring unplayed tracks, and weighted query search to support exploratory discovery and novelty maintenance.
positioning_summary: 本研究は既存の音楽プレーヤーが明確な選曲や受動的再生に偏っており、その中間に位置する利用者の潜在的な「旬」な音楽の収集・再生スタイルが支援されていないという問題を扱っている。本研究はPCで音楽を聴く利用者のうち一時的嗜好を持つ利用者や複数条件の重み付けで曲を集めたい利用者を対象に、そのギャップを埋めることを目的としている。
positioning_summary_en: This study addresses the gap that existing music players focus on explicit selection or passive playback and do not support users who want to collect and play "seasonal" music in an intermediate style. This study targets PC music listeners who have temporary preferences or who want to combine multiple weighted conditions to gather tracks and aims to fill that gap.
purpose_summary: 本研究は利用者が継続的に「旬」な音楽を発見して聴く喜びを提供することを目的としている。本研究は利用者が聴き飽きる問題を緩和し、探索的な嗜好をインタフェースで扱えるようにすることを具体的な目的としている。
purpose_summary_en: This study aims to provide users with the continuous enjoyment of discovering and listening to "seasonal" music. This study specifically aims to reduce listener fatigue and enable exploratory preferences to be handled via the interface.
method_summary: 本研究は収集型ミュージックプレーヤーの試作として本システムを提案し、アルバム単位のドラッグ＆ドロップによるプレイリスト操作と可視化を中心とした設計を行った。本システムは未聴曲を優先するシャッフル機能やいけすの開閉で流入量を調節する機能、複数検索クエリの重み付けやリアルタイムな絞り込み量調整などを実装している。
method_summary_en: This study proposed a prototype collection-based music player and designed the interface around album-level drag-and-drop playlist manipulation and visualization. This system implemented features such as shuffle prioritizing unplayed tracks, controls to adjust influx into playlists, and weighted multi-query search with real-time control of filtering amounts.
evaluation_summary: 本研究は著者による運用的な事例利用や簡易評価として約100枚のアルバムを用いたプロトタイプの使用を通じて評価を行った。本研究はその評価で本システムのインタフェースにより好み中心の再生と時折の新奇性の両立やプレイリストの開閉による新たな音楽発見が得られたことを報告する一方で参加者数や定量的指標の提示はなく操作性の問題（群操作の欠如など）も報告された。
evaluation_summary_en: This study evaluated the prototype through operational case use and a simple assessment using about 100 albums by the authors. This study reported that the evaluation showed the interface enabled a balance of preference-centered playback and occasional novelty and produced new music discoveries via playlist controls, while also noting a lack of participant numbers and quantitative metrics and reporting usability issues such as missing batch operations.

Title: IKESU: Music player for listening to "season" music
Authors: Takaaki Ishii, Arito Mochizuki, Takeshi Hoshino, Youichi Horry

Abstract: This study proposes an interface for PC music playback that helps users continuously discover and listen to "seasonal" music. This study implemented a prototype collection-based player with album-level visualization, shuffle favoring unplayed tracks, and weighted query search to support exploratory discovery and novelty maintenance.
Positioning Summary: This study addresses the gap that existing music players focus on explicit selection or passive playback and do not support users who want to collect and play "seasonal" music in an intermediate style. This study targets PC music listeners who have temporary preferences or who want to combine multiple weighted conditions to gather tracks and aims to fill that gap.
Purpose Summary: This study aims to provide users with the continuous enjoyment of discovering and listening to "seasonal" music. This study specifically aims to reduce listener fatigue and enable exploratory preferences to be handled via the interface.
Method Summary: This study proposed a prototype collection-based music player and designed the interface around album-level drag-and-drop playlist manipulation and visualization. This system implemented features such as shuffle prioritizing unplayed tracks, controls to adjust influx into playlists, and weighted multi-query search with real-time control of filtering amounts.
Evaluation Summary: This study evaluated the prototype through operational case use and a simple assessment using about 100 albums by the authors. This study reported that the evaluation showed the interface enabled a balance of preference-centered playback and occasional novelty and produced new music discoveries via playlist controls, while also noting a lack of participant numbers and quantitative metrics and reporting usability issues such as missing batch operations.
